english:
  title: 'The Biography of Chastity: The Story of Madam Cao'
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Madam Cao was from Sunyeong County. In the fifth month of Gyeongoh in the Zhiyuan era, when King Chunggyeong returned from Ganghwa to Songdo, General Hong Mun-gye and others executed treacherous ministers and restored royal authority. In the sixth month, the private armies of the fallen powers, led by the Divine Guard, seized the승화후 and plotted rebellion, forcing officials and soldiers who had not yet crossed the river onto ships bound southward. The vessels stretched endlessly before and behind.

    Madam Cao was but six years old, swept along in the throng with her father, Captain Cha Bi. The rebels had established false officials to tempt compliance, from ministers down to officers. Because Cha Bi possessed both cunning and strength, he was appointed commander. Through his wits, he managed to escape and return to the capital. When the rebels were defeated, women and children fell to blades and drowned in the sea, nearly all perished. The rest were captured by foreign armies. Yet all the old and young aboard Cha Bi's vessel survived whole. He returned and rejoined the royal army, pursuing the rebels to Tamla, where he died in the winter of Sinmi.

    At thirteen, Madam Cao was given to Captain Han Bok and bore him a daughter. Her father-in-law, the court official Kwang Su, fell in the eastern campaign against Japan in the summer of Sinsa. In the summer of Sinmyo, Han Bok too died in battle against the Khitans. Widowed before thirty, she lived fifty years alone. Day and night she labored with her needle and loom, clothing and feeding her daughter and grandchildren, providing for their security and the expenses of guests, weddings, funerals, and ancestral rites. Now seventy-seven, she remains vigorous and well. Her memory is sharp—she recounts events from the chaos of her youth and the rise and fall of kingdoms with perfect clarity, every detail intact.

    I dwell in what was once her home. Her granddaughter's husband, Inspector Li Yang-jik, was my fellow scholar and friend, so I have heard her story in full detail. Once, traveling through China, I observed monuments to chastity so numerous they seemed to stretch to every horizon. I wondered at their abundance. Upon reflection, I understood: the court sometimes raised monuments to women of means rather than virtue, and sometimes names were falsely registered to escape military service. The inspectors and censors constantly investigate such deceptions, revealing the government's noble intent to preserve human virtue and strengthen the morality of the people.

    Had Madam Cao's deeds come to the attention of the court, surely her name would have been inscribed in the great chronicles and honored throughout the land. How could such virtue fade into obscurity?

    The historian says: "A woman fulfills her duty by observing the three obediences. Here was a woman whose father and husband both gave their lives to the state, who bore no son, who became a widow in her youth and guarded her chastity unto old age—yet received no recognition from officials or commendation from men. How sorrowful! But Heaven's way is never thwarted. Thus she was granted health and longevity, as she surely deserved."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three obediences' (三從) refers to the traditional Confucian virtue whereby a woman obeys her father, then her husband, then her son in succession.
  - key: ''
    value: Tamla refers to the island of Jeju.
  - key: ''
    value: The mention of monuments to chastity reflects the Korean practice of erecting honorific gates and monuments (貞節坊) to commemorate virtuous widows who did not remarry.
